WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.280
Welcome to the Data Science Hangout. If you're joining for the first time, it's great to meet

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:17.799
you. I'm Rachel, I'm the host of the Hangout. If this is your first Hangout, this is an

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:23.840
open space for the whole data science community to connect and chat about data science leadership,

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:28.799
questions you're facing, what's going on in the world of data science. And so we want

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:33.480
this to be a space where everybody can participate and we can hear from everyone. So there's

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:38.680
three ways you can ask questions. You can always jump in live and just raise your hand

00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:45.000
on zoom that seems to be the easiest way. You could also put questions in the zoom chat

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.240
and just put a little star there if you want me to ask the question out loud if you're

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:54.759
maybe like in a coffee shop or something. And then we also have a Slido link where you

00:00:54.759 --> 00:01:02.439
can ask anonymous questions. And so Tyler or Rob will share that in just a second here.

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:06.320
Just want to reiterate, we love to hear from everyone no matter your level of experience

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:13.639
to or, or the industry that you work in. But I'm so happy to be joined by my co host for

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:21.720
today, Joe Gibson. Joe is a senior project director at the Beaumont Foundation, and former

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:27.360
director of epidemiology at Marion County Public Health Department. And Joe, I'd love

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:32.720
to have you jump in here and introduce yourself and maybe share a little bit about your role

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:34.720
in the foundation.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:40.040
Sure. So I've been at Beaumont just since December, so it's not that long. We're working

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:48.680
on a really interesting project to develop health centered local data ecosystems that

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:53.080
already exist all over the place. I mean, there's already health data at any location

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:58.839
that gets used by different people for different purposes, but try to develop those so that

00:01:58.839 --> 00:02:05.160
they're more focused on equity and anti-racism with a lot of community engagement to guide

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:11.199
the use of that data, especially engagement by communities that are generally marginalized.

00:02:11.199 --> 00:02:17.440
So try to focus the use of that data toward identifying structural racism and addressing

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:25.720
issues of structural racism, bring the data more to bear on those issues. So anyway, that's

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:30.240
what I'm doing at Beaumont, and I'm just kind of informatics advisor as well there. But

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:37.800
I've spent 18 years as Indianapolis's epidemiology program director within the Marion County

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:42.240
Public Health Department and been very involved nationally in trying to improve public health

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:47.880
informatics, essentially. A lot of partnership with healthcare informatics. We've got the

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:53.199
Regenstrief Institute here in Indianapolis, which is a real leader in terms of clinical

00:02:53.199 --> 00:02:54.199
informatics.

00:02:54.199 --> 00:03:01.440
Thanks, Joe, and thanks for all that you're doing in this space, too. I know I actually

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:07.199
was introduced to you by Jennifer, who comes to the Hangout quite a bit, and she had let

00:03:07.199 --> 00:03:14.119
me know how you had grown the team from one to 17 epidemiologists back when you worked

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:19.440
together at the Public Health Department, and I'd love to just kind of hear a little

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:23.759
bit about how you did that and your journey in doing so.

00:03:23.759 --> 00:03:30.440
A lot of the credit goes to our director. She really values data, and I came in, you

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:36.240
know, I'm just a data geek. There were four people in the group, and I just started organizing

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:41.759
our data sets into a central area, trying to link data together and trying to amass

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:46.119
more data and organize it so we can be very responsive to any sort of data requests that

00:03:46.119 --> 00:03:52.960
came through from the director, from all our community partners, all the, in public health,

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:55.559
public health only works for partnerships, so there's all sorts of people in the community

00:03:55.559 --> 00:04:02.080
who are concerned with health and are trying to get grants to improve health clinics, you

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:06.479
know, a hunger network, all sorts of groups like that, so we tried to set up systems so

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:11.479
we could really quickly respond to their needs, and so we were able to use mainly SAS, and

00:04:11.479 --> 00:04:15.880
then we got into R to organize the data sets and present the data out to the community

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:19.799
and then partner with a lot of other local sort of data-oriented organizations where

00:04:19.799 --> 00:04:24.279
we could give them data and they could create interfaces to it as well.

00:04:24.279 --> 00:04:30.200
Just over time, just by being valuable, by pulling in more grants, the group slowly grew.

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:37.000
I was there 18 years, so the growth from about four to about 20 was over 18 years.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.600
About half of that was through grants and about half of that was through general fund

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:44.440
from the health department because we were valuable.

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:47.519
That's awesome.

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:56.320
What was that process like of getting people on board to use SAS and then R?

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:59.000
It was interesting.

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:02.760
It's always so hard when you hire somebody to really have a good assessment of their

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:10.000
skills, and we were constantly trying to figure out how to assess skills as we hired people.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.519
You know, we'd have various, you know, at first it was around SAS, and so we had sort

00:05:14.519 --> 00:05:18.000
of this question about people's experience and skills in SAS, and we'd ask them very

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.399
specific to do specific tasks around SAS, and I remember somebody who did really well

00:05:24.399 --> 00:05:30.279
in the quiz but turned out not to just sort of have a mind for doing the programming,

00:05:30.279 --> 00:05:36.160
and other folks who didn't especially do well on those quizzes and just grokked the program

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:37.760
and were able to do amazing things.

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:45.720
So never really cracked that nut, but always had a lot of support within the group, so

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:50.160
we tried to create a really open environment where people were expected to ask for help

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:57.640
from other people, that nobody was, working on your own was not a good thing.

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:01.000
We had to balance that with some people just wanting to sort of, learning by discovering

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:07.320
themselves, but I really tried to push people to ask questions, and we set up systems where

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:12.760
everybody's code got reviewed by somebody else in the group, which was, in part it was

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:18.000
a quality check, but more it probably provided value by helping people see different approaches

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:19.000
to coding.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.640
So if somebody took one approach and somebody else comes in, they go, oh, you know, I'm

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:25.679
learning something from your code, or they're looking at code that could be improved and

00:06:25.679 --> 00:06:27.279
they're teaching somebody how to improve it.

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:33.600
So just a validation process we had for any work products being produced, the code had

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:38.600
to be audited, we called it a code audit, by somebody else.

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:43.519
That's been, that was a really good learning tool within the group to bring people along

00:06:43.519 --> 00:06:45.559
in their programming.

00:06:45.559 --> 00:06:49.839
And then we've tried to have an environment where people could just go, like, encourage

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:55.359
people to innovate and take chances and create things, and it's, you know, it was okay to

00:06:55.359 --> 00:07:00.279
make mistakes, but it wasn't okay not to try things.

00:07:00.279 --> 00:07:05.920
It sounds like a great culture on the team, just being able to go ask everyone questions

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:11.559
too, and I wonder how that differs with being in person and being able to work together

00:07:11.559 --> 00:07:18.279
versus now, like, working virtually too, or work some people in different locations.

00:07:18.279 --> 00:07:22.239
There are good and bad things about it, but in Net, I think we actually were more effective

00:07:22.239 --> 00:07:23.600
when we went virtual.

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:28.480
We used WebEx teams for, you know, chat, but, you know, everybody's got some sort of chat

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:30.679
tool.

00:07:30.679 --> 00:07:35.000
And that actually increased a lot of the interactions that we had with people, because it was so

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:40.320
easy to quickly send a message to somebody else about something.

00:07:40.359 --> 00:07:43.079
So, in Net, it was kind of a good thing.

00:07:43.079 --> 00:07:47.040
There's still a lot of challenges in sort of establishing the relationships, especially

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:51.920
when you hire new people, and it was all virtual to really make somebody feel like they're

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:57.559
part of a team, you know, we could have lunches together, which was always the highlight of

00:07:57.559 --> 00:07:58.559
the day.

00:07:58.559 --> 00:07:59.559
Yeah.

00:07:59.559 --> 00:08:06.079
Sometimes I struggle with knowing, like, if it's, when it's okay to ask people questions,

00:08:06.079 --> 00:08:11.679
like, virtually, like, through Slack, because I feel like I'm just, like, I don't know,

00:08:11.679 --> 00:08:16.079
interrupting people, which I am, but, or knowing what's the best way to do that too.

00:08:16.079 --> 00:08:19.640
Yeah, we had a couple of discussions in our staff meetings around that.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:20.640
What will be our protocol?

00:08:20.640 --> 00:08:21.640
What's acceptable?

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:22.640
What's not acceptable?

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:27.480
To try to encourage a reasonable amount of communication without people feeling imposed

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:28.480
upon.

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:30.480
So, we set some standards there.

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:36.400
I see there's an anonymous question that came in that says, did you have to deal with any

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:44.599
mistrust of open source tools when switching from SaaS to R?

00:08:44.599 --> 00:08:45.599
Not really.

00:08:45.599 --> 00:08:53.039
We, we had a lot of autonomy in terms of what tools we decided to use.

00:08:53.039 --> 00:08:59.919
So yeah, IT really didn't challenge that much.

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:01.039
I would say no.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:08.479
I might dig into this a bit deeper, because I was just on a call yesterday with three

00:09:08.479 --> 00:09:15.119
people who were having struggles with convincing IT or just, like, bringing open source tools

00:09:15.119 --> 00:09:15.679
to IT.

00:09:17.919 --> 00:09:19.760
How did you introduce it to them?

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:22.640
We just asked for it.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:26.159
I mean, but this was, this is only, we only got heavily into R.

00:09:26.239 --> 00:09:31.760
We got very heavily into R during the COVID pandemic, just early on in that, because the

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:36.559
visualization interface was just a lot easier for us to work with in SaaS and to expand

00:09:36.559 --> 00:09:37.119
upon.

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:43.919
But we'd started dabbling in R just, just like five or seven years ago.

00:09:43.919 --> 00:09:49.760
And by that point, our IT group, which is a great, great group, really a lot of forward

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:54.000
thinking people in it, was pretty open already to open source, you know.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.640
So it wasn't, there really wasn't a lot of questions.

00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:58.960
They just, we said, this is something we need.

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:01.119
They said, okay, set it up.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:03.200
They weren't happy.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:05.520
They wanted, they wanted to stay on Windows systems.

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:10.239
So, you know, we didn't get to use some of the Linux stuff, which might have made some

00:10:10.239 --> 00:10:14.320
things easier, except that they just wanted one OS to maintain.

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:15.460
Yeah.

00:10:16.719 --> 00:10:21.359
Well, I hope everybody has that, that good of an experience too.

00:10:21.359 --> 00:10:22.320
We had a great IT group.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:23.760
We were, we're very fortunate.

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:25.520
That's great.

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.239
Does anybody have questions about that?

00:10:28.239 --> 00:10:30.479
Or is like experiencing this right now?

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:36.719
Rachel, I, I can chat about that, but I don't want to monopolize anything.

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:40.239
We're going through it constantly and we're in our, yeah.

00:10:40.239 --> 00:10:47.119
So like, I, I feel the pain of where the question has come from.

00:10:47.119 --> 00:10:49.359
I've had it in many places and we're doing it now.

00:10:49.599 --> 00:10:54.880
And it just, tomorrow I have a architectural review board.

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:58.719
Why are you considering using R for pipelines into GCP?

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:03.679
Just like those questions because IT don't understand, right?

00:11:03.679 --> 00:11:08.239
Like how is a stats language a thing to do stuff with data pipelines?

00:11:09.039 --> 00:11:10.159
There's a lot of education.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:16.880
And like people think of R, sorry if I say this, but sorry, not sorry.

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:18.000
It's 1985 R.

00:11:18.799 --> 00:11:21.919
Well, it's moved on a little bit since I know the language.

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:26.880
It was created in the early nineties, but like they think of it as that timeframe.

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:28.000
It's not the same anymore.

00:11:30.559 --> 00:11:30.799
Yeah.

00:11:30.799 --> 00:11:34.080
It sounds like it can be so different across the board, depending on

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:38.159
the industry that you're in or just the company itself.

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:41.039
Javier, I see you had your hand raised too.

00:11:41.039 --> 00:11:41.840
If you want to jump in.

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:46.799
Yeah, I was just going to add at, at my last company,

00:11:46.799 --> 00:11:49.919
this was like a fairly regular conversation

00:11:49.919 --> 00:11:54.239
because there was a cohort of kind of your classical statisticians

00:11:54.239 --> 00:11:57.039
that were just very comfortable doing their work in SAS.

00:11:57.840 --> 00:11:59.919
And we got around that.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:04.719
I mean, they still use SAS to a certain extent,

00:12:04.719 --> 00:12:09.840
but having like very tailored walkthroughs of things you can do

00:12:10.559 --> 00:12:14.239
with R for like very specific teams.

00:12:14.239 --> 00:12:17.760
So like, Hey, let's look at your workflow right now

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:19.760
and let's see how we could do this in R.

00:12:21.039 --> 00:12:22.880
That always seemed to really impress,

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:25.599
especially when you kind of wrapped it around R Markdown

00:12:25.599 --> 00:12:30.239
or something to like, you know, very quickly and cleanly present your data.

00:12:32.559 --> 00:12:35.440
So, yeah, I think just having these one-on-one

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:39.359
kind of smaller trainings with these groups of SAS users,

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:42.320
like here, here's how you do it in SAS.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:43.679
Let me show you how you could do it in R.

00:12:43.679 --> 00:12:44.799
I think that goes a long way.

00:12:47.599 --> 00:12:48.159
Definitely.

00:12:49.599 --> 00:12:51.599
We're trying to get people into R.

00:12:52.159 --> 00:12:54.000
We did some of that stuff as well.

00:12:55.679 --> 00:12:58.799
I was just spotting whether people would pick up on it.

00:12:58.799 --> 00:13:01.520
Each of our ethies is pretty independent in their programming.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:02.960
I mean, we have those code outs and stuff,

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:04.640
but in terms of their assignments,

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:07.200
they can choose what they want to use for what they're doing.

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:13.440
And it was hard to get people to dig in to a new system.

00:13:13.679 --> 00:13:15.359
Because, you know, it's easy to use what you know.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:20.479
But once we did, some people really took to it.

00:13:23.359 --> 00:13:27.760
On that topic too, I see, Ethan, you just asked a question as well

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:29.840
about when you have people using different tools.

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:30.960
Do you want to jump in?

00:13:31.919 --> 00:13:34.880
Yeah, so I just want to ask that within your team,

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:37.520
you mentioned that people use both SAS and R.

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:40.400
Do you have situations where some people are really into SAS

00:13:40.400 --> 00:13:42.239
and people are really into R?

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:46.080
How do you manage considering you're still code reviewing each other?

00:13:46.080 --> 00:13:48.159
Because this is speaking from my experience,

00:13:48.159 --> 00:13:52.400
and I have colleagues, we use not SAS, but SPSS.

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:57.359
But we have people who have 10, 20 years of experience doing SPSS,

00:13:57.359 --> 00:14:01.039
and it's difficult to teach old dog new tricks.

00:14:01.039 --> 00:14:04.719
So it's difficult to get people to switch on to new stuff.

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:10.239
Yeah, and that would come down to who you choose to do your code review.

00:14:10.799 --> 00:14:14.320
So we had a system where you kind of rotate through everybody.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:18.000
But if it's going to be some complicated piece of R,

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.080
then you've got to, there's just a limited number of people

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:20.880
that are going to do it.

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:22.320
Same with SAS.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:24.479
I mean, we didn't have people use SAS,

00:14:24.479 --> 00:14:28.239
but we didn't have a whole lot of people who were super experts in SAS.

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:32.239
So it just came down to who was going to be doing the code review there.

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:37.200
Again, though, it was a great opportunity for discovery

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:38.719
and for people to see what was possible.

00:14:39.679 --> 00:14:43.679
So I think, again, about COVID, about the, we created a dashboard,

00:14:43.679 --> 00:14:48.000
which I wouldn't, I brag about how great the functionality was

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.960
and how it looked, but we're not, we weren't expert enough

00:14:50.960 --> 00:14:53.359
to actually create a dashboard that would load quickly.

00:14:53.359 --> 00:14:56.320
So it takes like 30 seconds to load, and then it's amazing.

00:14:58.719 --> 00:15:03.039
But when people saw what was possible, it would get them excited.

00:15:03.039 --> 00:15:05.200
And then if you could show them how simple it was

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:09.119
to add a new graph or something, that could get them engaged as well.

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:16.000
I see there was another anonymous question too,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.599
that was, can Joe and or other people on the call too,

00:15:19.599 --> 00:15:24.880
give an example or two of guidelines they have as far as,

00:15:24.880 --> 00:15:26.799
sorry, just trying to read this question,

00:15:26.799 --> 00:15:31.760
as far as questions using chat now that we are virtual, was that helpful?

00:15:32.719 --> 00:15:35.520
And if anyone has other context to add to that question,

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:37.840
please put it in the chat too.

00:15:39.679 --> 00:15:43.679
But I think it's just around like guidelines that you mentioned

00:15:43.679 --> 00:15:47.919
for like slacking people with questions now that we're all virtual.

00:15:48.799 --> 00:15:52.719
Right, and just to, if I can, I'll try to remember what our guidelines were,

00:15:52.719 --> 00:15:57.119
but they were essentially first text somebody, don't call them,

00:15:57.119 --> 00:15:59.919
don't do a voice call, first text them to see if they're available.

00:16:00.239 --> 00:16:03.520
And then do a voice call and you call them if they don't respond,

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:04.799
depending on the urgency or not.

00:16:05.679 --> 00:16:09.440
And we'd use email for anything that needs to have a long-term record,

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:10.559
you have to, you do an email,

00:16:10.559 --> 00:16:13.119
because that's the only place that we have long-term records.

00:16:13.679 --> 00:16:18.479
But to prefer for quick communication to use a Slack chat

00:16:18.479 --> 00:16:20.719
and or whatever, a WebEx chat.

00:16:21.919 --> 00:16:24.640
And that was to be used at any time.

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:26.880
And people should at least acknowledge,

00:16:27.039 --> 00:16:28.400
at least respond when they've seen it,

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:29.679
so you know that somebody's seen it.

00:16:31.679 --> 00:16:34.000
That was about the extent of our guidance as I remember it.

00:16:36.799 --> 00:16:41.679
Yeah, we've been talking about it a lot here at our studio too.

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:46.239
Like when you put a message into a channel that has a bunch of people,

00:16:46.239 --> 00:16:49.440
like everybody then starts to like try and answer the question

00:16:50.159 --> 00:16:53.359
instead of if it's just like targeted at one person

00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:55.440
or the specific people that need to see it.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
So we're working on that now.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.280
That was another mistake I made early in the pandemic

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:05.520
was when we switched to starting using WebEx chat.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:08.319
I said, okay, there's a bunch of joke.

00:17:08.319 --> 00:17:10.800
And I was like, okay, well, let's use this channel to get work done.

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:15.119
And then after about a month, I was like, boy, that was a mistake.

00:17:15.119 --> 00:17:17.119
We got to have a channel where we're talking to each other.

00:17:17.119 --> 00:17:17.680
We're all remote.

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:19.680
We got to have some social interaction here.

00:17:20.719 --> 00:17:21.219
Yeah.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
Angela, I think you're going to have a question.

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:27.760
Angela, I see you had asked a question in the chat earlier

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:30.719
about using RStudio Cloud.

00:17:31.439 --> 00:17:36.079
But I'm curious to just hear some more context of how you might use it.

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:41.280
Yeah, so I should probably do a little bit of an introduction.

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:44.079
Thanks for the welcomingness to like whatever scale

00:17:44.079 --> 00:17:46.239
or whatever amount of work we do with this.

00:17:47.199 --> 00:17:50.640
So I am the Water Resources Planner for Penobscot Indian Nation

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:52.000
in what is Central Maine.

00:17:52.479 --> 00:17:57.359
And so we've been using R for a long time to do a variety of things.

00:17:57.359 --> 00:18:01.199
But I also work with a group, a tribal exchange network group,

00:18:01.199 --> 00:18:02.640
which we just deal with tribe.

00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:06.239
We help tribes all across the country doing environmental monitoring,

00:18:07.199 --> 00:18:08.400
help process their data.

00:18:09.119 --> 00:18:12.560
And the reason I asked about RStudio Cloud is for a variety of reasons.

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:17.680
Anytime we do training, it's a real hassle to get everybody set up.

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:20.239
And there's inevitably problems in any session.

00:18:21.199 --> 00:18:23.199
And then when people go back, frankly,

00:18:23.199 --> 00:18:25.199
just what you guys were talking about, IT issues,

00:18:25.920 --> 00:18:27.280
it can just be such a pain.

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:29.520
And I just didn't know if anybody had any experience.

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:32.079
I haven't looked into it enough,

00:18:32.079 --> 00:18:38.079
whether you can have data hosted locally and use RStudio to ingest it

00:18:38.079 --> 00:18:39.359
or whether your data has to be online.

00:18:39.359 --> 00:18:40.719
I mean, there's so many questions,

00:18:40.719 --> 00:18:45.520
but I really feel like it might be a solution for a lot of tribes.

00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:47.760
Mind you, we have to have internet connection,

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:49.920
which is not always the case, especially up in Alaska.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.880
But I guess I'm trying to figure out how we can help train people,

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:59.199
but also how we can help have people something easier when they go home

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:00.719
that they don't have to call us up and go,

00:19:00.719 --> 00:19:02.400
all right, this isn't working.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:03.760
So any thoughts would be great.

00:19:07.359 --> 00:19:08.959
I know, oh, there you go.

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:11.599
Just say we didn't use RStudio Cloud,

00:19:11.599 --> 00:19:16.319
but we've used a lot of online trainings that are fairly self-contained

00:19:16.959 --> 00:19:18.560
that have been really useful.

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:23.280
Just, you know, R Markdown stuff and with available data sets

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:25.680
that people are just important and use on their own systems.

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:32.400
There's a lot of webinars that I can share with you, Angela,

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:34.560
about getting started with RStudio Cloud

00:19:34.560 --> 00:19:36.800
if you do want to try it out too

00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:39.680
for other people that have used it for trainings.

00:19:40.319 --> 00:19:42.319
But I know that's like a huge benefit

00:19:42.319 --> 00:19:46.000
is that everybody has the environment already set up

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:47.439
with the packages that they need.

00:19:47.439 --> 00:19:51.680
So if it's someone brand new to using R,

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:53.520
they don't kind of get stuck in,

00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:55.119
how do I even install this thing?

00:19:55.839 --> 00:19:58.000
Yeah, that's what we're running into.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.160
So if you could send me stuff, that would be great, Rachel.

00:20:00.800 --> 00:20:03.439
That's really the biggest problem is most of the folks,

00:20:03.439 --> 00:20:05.520
not everybody, but most of the folks

00:20:05.520 --> 00:20:10.160
we are training and working with haven't done much coding at all.

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:12.640
And so they're really starting off in the beginning.

00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:16.000
And I love R.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.319
My boss has actually asked if maybe I would get R

00:20:18.319 --> 00:20:20.000
to make a cup of coffee for me someday.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.839
So I've told him that that's my goal.

00:20:21.839 --> 00:20:27.280
But not everybody has that level of addiction, I guess.

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:32.079
So it really can be almost like,

00:20:32.079 --> 00:20:34.079
oh, I don't want to use R

00:20:34.079 --> 00:20:37.520
because I can't deal with the complications.

00:20:37.520 --> 00:20:38.400
And I'm interested.

00:20:38.400 --> 00:20:39.760
I can't remember who it was that said,

00:20:39.760 --> 00:20:40.800
I think it was Brian that said,

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:43.760
you have some hacks for installing

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:45.199
and if you don't have administrative privileges.

00:20:45.439 --> 00:20:46.400
That's the first level.

00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:49.760
And then all the other upgrading versions of R,

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:51.920
it just can be a little bit daunting.

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:53.040
So thanks.

00:20:55.520 --> 00:20:56.319
Yeah, definitely.

00:20:56.319 --> 00:20:57.599
Thanks for the question.

00:20:57.599 --> 00:20:59.439
And Mike, I might put you on the spot here

00:20:59.439 --> 00:21:02.239
because it sounds like you have experience doing that.

00:21:02.239 --> 00:21:04.560
I see you put, it's brilliant for training.

00:21:06.319 --> 00:21:10.400
Yeah, so I've used it internally

00:21:11.119 --> 00:21:12.400
for doing training with colleagues.

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:17.119
As you say, even with the best will in the world

00:21:17.119 --> 00:21:19.199
and a lot of lead time,

00:21:21.839 --> 00:21:24.560
if you rely on individuals installing R

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:26.239
and installing packages,

00:21:26.239 --> 00:21:29.439
you're going to get a whole mess of different versions,

00:21:29.439 --> 00:21:31.439
different package versions, different package sets.

00:21:32.239 --> 00:21:35.839
Guaranteed, you'll spend half of the training time

00:21:35.839 --> 00:21:39.359
ironing out why this isn't working for a certain individual

00:21:39.359 --> 00:21:41.359
because who knows what.

00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:44.959
Whereas if you pop open RStudio Cloud,

00:21:44.959 --> 00:21:45.760
as you're saying, Rachel,

00:21:46.800 --> 00:21:49.680
you can set it up so that you guarantee

00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:53.680
everyone's got the same packages, versions, sets,

00:21:54.640 --> 00:21:58.479
ready to go and it just cuts out that hole.

00:21:58.479 --> 00:22:00.880
Now, why are you seeing this not working for you?

00:22:01.599 --> 00:22:08.000
I have to say that we had a few issues with it

00:22:08.079 --> 00:22:11.520
when I was being a classroom assistant

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:15.359
in the tidyverse training at RStudio conference in 2020.

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:20.000
I think that was almost a glitch.

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:22.479
Something in behind the scenes wasn't working

00:22:23.439 --> 00:22:25.520
just as it should on that occasion.

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:27.680
So it was causing a little bit of glitchiness.

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:32.479
But even then, it's by far the easiest way

00:22:32.479 --> 00:22:34.959
of just ensuring that everyone's seeing the same things

00:22:34.959 --> 00:22:36.079
and working off the same basis.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:39.439
Awesome.

00:22:39.439 --> 00:22:41.040
On that topic of training too,

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:42.560
I see there was anonymous question.

00:22:43.439 --> 00:22:46.319
What are a few starter packages or skills

00:22:46.319 --> 00:22:48.479
for teams that are transitioning languages?

00:22:50.959 --> 00:22:52.719
And I think, Joe, this might even,

00:22:52.719 --> 00:22:54.880
this might be a bit on SAS to R too.

00:22:55.439 --> 00:23:00.160
Yeah, we, so we had an epigroup,

00:23:00.160 --> 00:23:03.439
we had whatever, 15, yeah,

00:23:03.439 --> 00:23:04.719
the number of people in varied,

00:23:04.719 --> 00:23:07.199
but we had good control over that environment.

00:23:07.199 --> 00:23:09.439
And so we had everybody installing the same version.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.239
And we really pushed everyone

00:23:12.239 --> 00:23:17.119
to be using tidyverse packages as much as possible.

00:23:17.119 --> 00:23:18.719
Because my big concern with R

00:23:18.719 --> 00:23:20.079
is that there are so many packages.

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:23.439
If we've got people doing code audits for each other,

00:23:23.439 --> 00:23:24.959
I don't want to have everyone have to learn

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:28.079
everyone else's idiosyncratic favorite package.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:30.479
So we tried to have a lot of push

00:23:30.479 --> 00:23:32.319
toward using the same set of packages.

00:23:32.319 --> 00:23:36.079
And tidyverse is really nice and comprehensive and such.

00:23:36.079 --> 00:23:37.920
And we're into the graphics a lot as well.

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:40.479
So a lot of ggplot2 code.

00:23:44.479 --> 00:23:48.319
And so, I don't know, that's how we dealt with the package

00:23:48.319 --> 00:23:50.560
and the different environment issue.

00:23:50.560 --> 00:23:52.479
And again, it was just one group.

00:23:52.479 --> 00:23:53.599
So we're mainly just training that.

00:23:53.599 --> 00:23:55.359
We worked with the state health department

00:23:55.359 --> 00:23:56.800
to get them trained in R too.

00:23:56.800 --> 00:23:58.400
And we kind of, and they helped us.

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:00.000
And we did some sharing there.

00:24:01.439 --> 00:24:03.199
In terms of the transition from SAS though,

00:24:03.839 --> 00:24:08.880
I was, we never really had a wonderful training solution.

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:10.880
We had, we just had people from the group

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:12.800
put together trainings and present it

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:15.439
or find trainings online and present those to the group.

00:24:15.439 --> 00:24:17.920
And again, it was, here's an example

00:24:17.920 --> 00:24:18.719
of how you do it in SAS.

00:24:18.719 --> 00:24:19.599
Here's how you do it in R.

00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:21.760
Books that showed that sort of thing.

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:24.160
There's people going through examples

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:26.800
or the one-on-one code audit kind of trainings that we did.

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:29.280
No great solutions there from us.

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:29.839
Thanks, Joe.

00:24:29.839 --> 00:24:32.880
There's a few other anonymous questions too,

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:36.160
but again, feel free to jump in live into the conversation

00:24:36.160 --> 00:24:38.479
if you want to just raise your hand on Zoom too.

00:24:40.479 --> 00:24:43.040
But one of the questions was,

00:24:43.040 --> 00:24:44.640
how do you manage a team

00:24:45.199 --> 00:24:48.239
where there are different preferences for languages?

00:24:48.959 --> 00:24:52.479
So we stayed very organized in our code.

00:24:52.479 --> 00:24:54.560
And any work product we got produced

00:24:55.119 --> 00:24:57.119
had to have a lot of language.

00:24:57.199 --> 00:24:58.239
So any work product that we got produced

00:24:58.239 --> 00:24:59.920
had to have code.

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:01.040
It was archived.

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:03.920
It went into a repository and it got changed.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:05.680
That changes when it's a repository.

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:08.319
So we had a lot of controls

00:25:08.319 --> 00:25:10.400
so we could always do what I call a data audit.

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:12.079
Any work product that we produced

00:25:12.079 --> 00:25:13.359
over the 18 years I was there,

00:25:13.920 --> 00:25:15.439
you could take that work product,

00:25:15.439 --> 00:25:17.520
there'd be an identifier on it

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:19.839
and you could track that back to the code

00:25:19.839 --> 00:25:21.520
that produced that data thing.

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:22.400
So if there's a problem with it,

00:25:22.400 --> 00:25:23.839
we can figure out what the problem was.

00:25:23.839 --> 00:25:25.199
Or if you wanted to reproduce it,

00:25:25.199 --> 00:25:26.640
you could find the source code

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:28.000
and you could update that

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:29.119
and use that code again.

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:33.599
So I've lost track of the question.

00:25:33.599 --> 00:25:34.099
I'm sorry.

00:25:36.079 --> 00:25:38.000
It was just around managing the team

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:39.359
where there's different preferences.

00:25:39.359 --> 00:25:44.000
So we built this code library

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.400
that had a foundation

00:25:46.400 --> 00:25:48.079
and sort of evolving code

00:25:48.079 --> 00:25:50.000
for different functions that we often did.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:51.040
By the time I left there,

00:25:51.040 --> 00:25:53.439
there were thousands of programs in this library,

00:25:53.439 --> 00:25:54.800
but they're tracked in a database

00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:55.439
and you could search it

00:25:55.439 --> 00:25:57.760
and you could find useful code.

00:25:57.760 --> 00:26:00.319
And it didn't really matter if you use SAS or R.

00:26:00.319 --> 00:26:02.000
It was just to get the work done.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:03.680
I mean, I didn't really care.

00:26:04.800 --> 00:26:06.880
I mean, I really wanted the group to move toward R.

00:26:06.880 --> 00:26:08.640
I was kind of hoping long-term

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:10.239
we could bounce off the SAS

00:26:10.239 --> 00:26:12.160
and maybe even get to like

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:14.079
just having a Python R environment

00:26:14.079 --> 00:26:16.400
just to get to free programs

00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:18.000
that we could share with other public health agencies

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:18.959
and sort of move the whole

00:26:19.680 --> 00:26:22.319
public health informatics world forward

00:26:22.319 --> 00:26:23.920
by being able to share code more freely

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:27.040
and not be limited by some of the costs involved with SAS.

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:30.479
But I didn't care if people used R or SAS.

00:26:30.479 --> 00:26:32.079
And we created code

00:26:32.079 --> 00:26:34.400
that would allow people to call R from SAS

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:35.439
or SAS from R

00:26:35.439 --> 00:26:37.199
to try to go back between the two.

00:26:37.199 --> 00:26:38.959
And we had a lot of model code

00:26:38.959 --> 00:26:40.800
for using the two of them together

00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:42.479
to take advantage of some of our graphics

00:26:42.479 --> 00:26:44.319
and some of the SAS data management.

00:26:45.359 --> 00:26:47.280
But we didn't have rules about it.

00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:49.920
And we didn't have like an FDA breathing down our necks

00:26:49.920 --> 00:26:52.160
to say you have to conform to this or that.

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:53.520
We were free to do whatever

00:26:53.520 --> 00:26:54.959
we decided the standards would be.

00:26:57.479 --> 00:26:58.640
For sure.

00:26:59.520 --> 00:27:02.400
I know something you're especially passionate about

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:04.719
is improving the public health system.

00:27:04.719 --> 00:27:07.839
And I'm curious if there's ways

00:27:07.839 --> 00:27:10.959
that we as a community can come together

00:27:10.959 --> 00:27:12.640
to help do that

00:27:12.640 --> 00:27:14.800
or what ideas you have for doing this.

00:27:16.079 --> 00:27:17.920
There's some exciting stuff going on

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:19.359
in public health informatics

00:27:19.359 --> 00:27:21.040
around R,

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:24.560
around just open source data sharing.

00:27:26.160 --> 00:27:28.160
They're kind of one-off initiatives

00:27:28.160 --> 00:27:29.119
for the most part.

00:27:29.119 --> 00:27:33.199
But there are folks who have GitHub sites

00:27:33.199 --> 00:27:34.239
where they're sharing their code.

00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:36.560
There are some communities of practice.

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:37.359
There's one around,

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:39.359
they're called syndromic surveillance,

00:27:39.359 --> 00:27:41.680
but essentially looking

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:43.119
at emergency department data.

00:27:43.119 --> 00:27:44.479
There's a national system

00:27:44.479 --> 00:27:46.160
and there's a lot of local systems

00:27:46.160 --> 00:27:47.599
that pull in emergency department data

00:27:47.599 --> 00:27:50.719
and look at it for emergencies

00:27:50.719 --> 00:27:51.280
that are occurring

00:27:51.280 --> 00:27:53.280
or suddenly there's a bunch of this disease

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:53.920
or that disease.

00:27:53.920 --> 00:27:54.959
We're tracking COVID.

00:27:54.959 --> 00:27:56.560
There's all sorts of very useful things

00:27:56.560 --> 00:27:57.839
you can do in emergency department data

00:27:57.839 --> 00:27:59.119
to get a more real-time picture

00:27:59.119 --> 00:28:00.560
of what's going on in your community.

00:28:01.439 --> 00:28:03.040
And there's a community of practice around that.

00:28:03.040 --> 00:28:04.239
And the community of practice

00:28:04.959 --> 00:28:07.040
has a group within it

00:28:07.040 --> 00:28:10.640
that's doing a lot of sharing of R code

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:12.160
for analyzing this data

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:13.760
and some kind of standards for it.

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:17.359
And there's a unified national platform

00:28:17.680 --> 00:28:18.880
that has some of the data

00:28:18.880 --> 00:28:20.640
and they're sharing R code

00:28:20.640 --> 00:28:22.079
for going up to that platform

00:28:22.079 --> 00:28:25.119
and analyzing your locker of data from that

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:27.680
and sessions about how to,

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:32.560
I mean, so I guess I see the opportunities.

00:28:32.560 --> 00:28:34.239
There's exciting stuff going on.

00:28:34.239 --> 00:28:35.520
How this community might help

00:28:35.520 --> 00:28:37.839
is just participating

00:28:37.839 --> 00:28:38.719
in community of practice.

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:41.599
They work because people engage in them.

00:28:41.599 --> 00:28:43.359
I mean, you guys have one right here.

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:46.239
So being engaged in a community of practice,

00:28:46.239 --> 00:28:46.800
supporting it,

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:49.920
moving into getting very involved

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:51.520
and helping to move things forward,

00:28:51.520 --> 00:28:53.760
lead things, take initiative

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:55.599
and really get engaged.

00:28:56.479 --> 00:28:58.880
I've got to say my own career really comes,

00:28:59.680 --> 00:29:00.640
I am where I am now

00:29:00.640 --> 00:29:02.319
because of communities of practice.

00:29:02.319 --> 00:29:03.439
I started in public health

00:29:04.800 --> 00:29:08.400
back when people wrote with chisels and stones,

00:29:08.400 --> 00:29:11.520
but I evolved to where I am now,

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:13.760
which is I'm very involved nationally

00:29:13.760 --> 00:29:14.560
in a lot of stuff

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:16.319
because of communities of practice

00:29:16.319 --> 00:29:18.479
by it's sort of the duocracy,

00:29:18.479 --> 00:29:20.479
the people who do come into power,

00:29:20.479 --> 00:29:21.680
you get engaged,

00:29:21.680 --> 00:29:22.880
you see what has to happen,

00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:23.920
you try to move it forward,

00:29:23.920 --> 00:29:24.800
you work with other people

00:29:24.800 --> 00:29:25.599
to make things happen

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:28.160
and you build things.

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:28.800
A lot of them fail

00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:29.760
and some of them don't work,

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:30.959
but you create a network

00:29:30.959 --> 00:29:32.239
that helps improve things.

00:29:35.599 --> 00:29:38.160
That's great that you have that community to it.

00:29:38.800 --> 00:29:41.520
We've been trying to like start some communities

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:43.520
or help start some communities of practice.

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:46.000
For example, for supply chain,

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:51.280
and I wonder how did they start that

00:29:51.280 --> 00:29:53.119
and then move it forward

00:29:53.119 --> 00:29:55.359
so that it's actually progressing?

00:30:00.319 --> 00:30:02.319
Did you, I don't know,

00:30:02.319 --> 00:30:04.719
just interested to hear how it started.

00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:08.719
I've been involved in trying

00:30:08.719 --> 00:30:09.760
to start communities of practice

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:12.239
that just fizzled and others that didn't.

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:15.680
Some of them take some of the ones,

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:17.119
the big one I think of that fizzled

00:30:17.119 --> 00:30:19.359
is because it was sort of attached

00:30:19.359 --> 00:30:23.199
to a research initiative that the CDC had.

00:30:23.199 --> 00:30:24.959
Suddenly the funding got pulled from it

00:30:24.959 --> 00:30:29.680
and so we were sort of the practice engine

00:30:29.680 --> 00:30:31.119
or the practice appendage

00:30:31.119 --> 00:30:31.760
that was attached

00:30:31.760 --> 00:30:33.520
to this sort of research community

00:30:33.520 --> 00:30:35.280
or research funded project

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:35.839
and that went away

00:30:35.839 --> 00:30:37.359
and so the appendage just sort of faded

00:30:38.479 --> 00:30:39.119
and that'll happen.

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:42.319
Life is full of risks

00:30:42.319 --> 00:30:44.160
and you invest and sometimes it doesn't pay off.

00:30:47.599 --> 00:30:48.560
It's got to be around something

00:30:48.560 --> 00:30:50.880
that people care enough to spend time doing.

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:54.640
There's got to be some immediate payoff to people

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:57.520
and I just, in my experience,

00:30:57.520 --> 00:30:58.079
I'm thinking about

00:30:58.079 --> 00:30:59.760
the National Public Health Association

00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:01.439
and work groups that we've had there.

00:31:04.719 --> 00:31:06.319
It's got to be something people care about

00:31:06.319 --> 00:31:07.599
but you've got to have enough,

00:31:07.599 --> 00:31:09.040
you've got to have a couple people

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:10.400
who are spending a lot of their time

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:12.239
thinking about the community

00:31:12.239 --> 00:31:13.680
and how to make the community work

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:15.040
and how to engage the community.

00:31:15.040 --> 00:31:16.079
I mean, I think Rachel,

00:31:16.079 --> 00:31:17.199
you probably have this role

00:31:17.199 --> 00:31:18.640
within this group of

00:31:19.199 --> 00:31:21.199
how do I do something

00:31:21.199 --> 00:31:22.160
that these people care about

00:31:22.160 --> 00:31:22.880
and bring them together

00:31:22.880 --> 00:31:24.239
so they get value out of the time

00:31:24.239 --> 00:31:25.599
so they're willing to come next week

00:31:25.599 --> 00:31:26.959
to do this again

00:31:26.959 --> 00:31:28.800
and then relationships start to happen

00:31:28.800 --> 00:31:29.760
because people start to meet

00:31:29.760 --> 00:31:30.959
and talk to each other

00:31:30.959 --> 00:31:33.199
and side projects start to build out of that

00:31:33.199 --> 00:31:34.239
and some of those fade

00:31:34.239 --> 00:31:35.359
and some of those are successful.

00:31:35.359 --> 00:31:36.640
There's value that comes out of that

00:31:36.640 --> 00:31:37.359
and it can grow

00:31:38.079 --> 00:31:39.599
but you really have to have the gardener.

00:31:39.599 --> 00:31:41.599
You have to have the person cultivating it

00:31:41.599 --> 00:31:44.000
or the several people cultivating it really

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.040
to create enough of a payoff

00:31:47.599 --> 00:31:48.560
kind of socially

00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:50.160
and value in terms of work

00:31:51.520 --> 00:31:52.560
that it moves forward

00:31:52.560 --> 00:31:53.280
and that only happens

00:31:53.280 --> 00:31:54.319
because people take a risk

00:31:54.319 --> 00:31:55.599
of investing their time

00:31:56.160 --> 00:31:56.959
in it.

00:31:56.959 --> 00:31:57.920
Somebody's got to gamble

00:31:57.920 --> 00:31:59.040
and put in that effort.

00:32:01.520 --> 00:32:03.520
Definitely, that's really helpful, Joe.

