a great question in the chat

00:34:01.760 --> 00:34:02.719
if you want to jump in.

00:34:05.839 --> 00:34:11.600
Hi, this is Stephanie, right?

00:34:12.159 --> 00:34:13.120
Yes, that's Stephanie.

00:34:15.840 --> 00:34:17.600
Oh, yeah, so I was really interested

00:34:17.600 --> 00:34:19.679
in how you were talking about, Jo,

00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:23.280
the code archive database

00:34:23.280 --> 00:34:23.840
you were mentioning,

00:34:23.840 --> 00:34:25.040
like tracking everything

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:27.439
because we've done a variety of things

00:34:27.439 --> 00:34:28.399
at different places I've worked

00:34:28.399 --> 00:34:29.760
and none of them have been

00:34:29.760 --> 00:34:31.439
particularly user-friendly.

00:34:31.600 --> 00:34:36.879
Yeah, and this is as user-friendly

00:34:36.879 --> 00:34:38.080
as we've gotten.

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:39.520
It still requires that each time

00:34:39.520 --> 00:34:40.959
that you create a work product

00:34:40.959 --> 00:34:43.199
that you log it into this database.

00:34:43.199 --> 00:34:44.320
So that's the trick,

00:34:44.320 --> 00:34:45.439
making sure that people log it.

00:34:45.439 --> 00:34:48.000
So when you start a work project,

00:34:48.560 --> 00:34:49.679
you go to the database,

00:34:49.679 --> 00:34:51.199
it creates a new ID

00:34:51.199 --> 00:34:52.239
for that work project.

00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:53.120
You put in a title,

00:34:53.120 --> 00:34:54.879
you put in just some basic information

00:34:54.879 --> 00:34:56.080
about the purpose of it.

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:56.719
It's not, you know,

00:34:56.719 --> 00:34:58.719
there's only like five fields

00:34:58.719 --> 00:34:59.439
you have to fill in.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:02.239
And then you hit a button

00:35:02.239 --> 00:35:03.360
that creates a folder for it.

00:35:03.360 --> 00:35:05.199
It kind of does some background setup

00:35:05.199 --> 00:35:06.239
to make things easier for you.

00:35:06.239 --> 00:35:07.439
And then you can store your stuff

00:35:07.439 --> 00:35:08.639
within the structure

00:35:08.639 --> 00:35:09.760
we've got on our network

00:35:09.760 --> 00:35:11.360
that allows people

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:12.239
to find things easily

00:35:12.239 --> 00:35:13.520
and is based on that ID.

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:15.360
And then that ID,

00:35:15.360 --> 00:35:17.360
you're responsible for that ID

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:18.239
on any work product

00:35:18.239 --> 00:35:20.080
or within the name of the files

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:21.679
that you create associated with this.

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:25.360
I'm not being really clear about that,

00:35:25.360 --> 00:35:26.560
but essentially the core of it

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:28.239
is there's an ID that's generated

00:35:28.239 --> 00:35:29.600
every time you do a work product.

00:35:30.159 --> 00:35:31.760
That ID is the first thing

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:33.040
in all the file names

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:34.399
associated with that product.

00:35:34.959 --> 00:35:35.840
For the most part,

00:35:35.840 --> 00:35:36.959
sometimes you have to put at the end

00:35:36.959 --> 00:35:38.239
because you want people,

00:35:38.239 --> 00:35:40.399
other people who aren't techies to read it.

00:35:40.399 --> 00:35:41.439
And it goes into a folder

00:35:41.439 --> 00:35:43.280
that's in a structure

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:44.080
where it makes it easy

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:45.439
to find all that information.

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:49.439
That's kind of the core of our system.

00:35:52.800 --> 00:35:54.800
Going back to,

00:35:54.800 --> 00:35:56.320
I know we were talking a lot about

00:35:56.879 --> 00:35:58.639
using different languages

00:35:58.639 --> 00:36:00.639
and how you manage people

00:36:00.639 --> 00:36:02.159
using different languages.

00:36:02.159 --> 00:36:03.360
But another question was,

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:05.760
how do you handle the situation

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:07.040
when something breaks

00:36:07.600 --> 00:36:08.800
and there isn't coverage

00:36:08.800 --> 00:36:10.560
across a specific language?

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:13.360
Like if somebody's out on PTO or something.

00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:19.439
We have enough people who know SAS and R

00:36:19.439 --> 00:36:20.320
that we figured it out.

00:36:20.959 --> 00:36:22.399
Part of that goes back

00:36:22.399 --> 00:36:23.439
to the documentation

00:36:24.560 --> 00:36:26.000
because there should be a record

00:36:26.159 --> 00:36:27.600
that explains what this program,

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:29.280
well, you get the work product,

00:36:29.280 --> 00:36:30.959
you can track it back to this ID,

00:36:30.959 --> 00:36:31.679
to the program.

00:36:32.639 --> 00:36:33.760
We have a standard header

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:34.719
that goes in each program

00:36:34.719 --> 00:36:36.000
that's supposed to explain

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:37.199
enough about that program

00:36:37.919 --> 00:36:38.879
that people should be able

00:36:38.879 --> 00:36:40.239
to work their way through it well enough.

00:36:40.959 --> 00:36:44.080
I really encourage,

00:36:44.080 --> 00:36:45.360
as a light way to put it,

00:36:45.360 --> 00:36:47.040
that people put comments in the program

00:36:47.040 --> 00:36:48.800
so that other people can read it.

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:50.080
You should, in my group,

00:36:50.080 --> 00:36:51.199
if you write a program,

00:36:51.199 --> 00:36:52.560
you should think about writing a program

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:53.919
to somebody else in the group.

00:36:53.919 --> 00:36:54.800
You're not writing a program

00:36:54.800 --> 00:36:55.520
to get something done.

00:36:55.520 --> 00:36:56.560
You're writing a program,

00:36:56.560 --> 00:36:57.840
yes, to get something done,

00:36:57.840 --> 00:36:58.879
but to get it done in a way

00:36:58.879 --> 00:36:59.679
where somebody else in the group

00:36:59.679 --> 00:37:00.320
can pick that up

00:37:00.320 --> 00:37:01.360
and understand what you're doing.

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:02.479
So there's got to be comments

00:37:02.479 --> 00:37:03.120
in your program.

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:05.840
And then we've got enough people

00:37:05.840 --> 00:37:06.639
who know SAS and R

00:37:06.639 --> 00:37:08.239
that we can figure it out

00:37:08.239 --> 00:37:09.360
for the most part.

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:10.000
It's a risk.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:10.800
It's a challenge,

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:13.760
but it hasn't been too bad

00:37:13.760 --> 00:37:15.760
because we do require

00:37:15.760 --> 00:37:17.600
some standards and documentation.

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:18.639
And again, that's a pain in the neck.

00:37:18.639 --> 00:37:20.080
It takes time and investment

00:37:20.080 --> 00:37:20.639
and people,

00:37:20.639 --> 00:37:22.959
you got to enforce people doing that.

00:37:23.679 --> 00:37:24.639
But the code audit

00:37:24.639 --> 00:37:25.919
helps with that as well.

00:37:25.919 --> 00:37:26.639
Part of the code audit

00:37:26.639 --> 00:37:27.840
is making sure that the program's

00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:29.919
clear enough and commented enough

00:37:29.919 --> 00:37:31.040
so people can understand it.

