until like six months ago.

00:39:20.560 --> 00:39:22.320
And I was shocked when I found out about it,

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:23.600
but super helpful.

00:39:23.600 --> 00:39:24.800
I have all kinds of snippets

00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:26.560
for myself and my team right now.

00:39:26.560 --> 00:39:30.080
Yeah, they live in a specific place

00:39:30.080 --> 00:39:31.679
within your kind of,

00:39:32.399 --> 00:39:34.080
I think it's within app data or something.

00:39:34.080 --> 00:39:36.959
So it's not terribly easy

00:39:36.959 --> 00:39:38.879
to share them between people.

00:39:38.879 --> 00:39:40.879
But if you're in an organization

00:39:40.879 --> 00:39:41.840
where you can roll out

00:39:43.679 --> 00:39:45.679
an installation or, you know,

00:39:46.239 --> 00:39:47.840
configurations like that,

00:39:47.840 --> 00:39:50.000
then they're a really helpful thing to know about.

00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:53.679
Okay, I'm going to admit

00:39:53.679 --> 00:39:55.360
I didn't know that either.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.719
So if you're in the RStudio IDE,

00:40:01.439 --> 00:40:03.040
when you start typing a function name

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:05.760
or something, you can use tab to auto-complete.

00:40:06.800 --> 00:40:08.639
But you basically give

00:40:08.639 --> 00:40:11.040
the little kind of template of code

00:40:11.679 --> 00:40:12.800
has its own little name.

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:15.040
And so if you hit tab,

00:40:15.679 --> 00:40:17.040
it will auto-suggest

00:40:17.040 --> 00:40:18.399
one of the things it will auto-suggest

00:40:18.399 --> 00:40:19.840
is either a function or a snippet.

00:40:20.719 --> 00:40:22.639
And then if you choose the snippet,

00:40:22.639 --> 00:40:26.239
then if it's like a ggplot framework,

00:40:26.239 --> 00:40:27.199
then it will say, you know,

00:40:27.199 --> 00:40:28.159
what's your data?

00:40:28.159 --> 00:40:29.760
What's the aesthetics?

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:32.000
And it kind of just guides you

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.719
through filling in the right information.

00:40:36.879 --> 00:40:38.159
And so, as I say,

00:40:38.159 --> 00:40:39.520
it's almost like a function,

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:42.000
except that it's just helping you.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:43.840
It's a framework for writing your code.

00:40:44.639 --> 00:40:48.959
Cool. I see Yan had asked a question to you, Mike,

00:40:48.959 --> 00:40:51.439
to share more on what you did with that.

00:40:51.439 --> 00:40:53.040
If you don't mind sharing, like,

00:40:53.600 --> 00:40:54.719
maybe some helpful links

00:40:54.719 --> 00:40:57.040
or resource you used for it.

00:40:57.040 --> 00:41:00.800
Yeah, I think Tatsu has just shared

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:04.399
the code snippets article, which is great.

00:41:06.399 --> 00:41:08.000
I haven't used them in Anger.

00:41:08.560 --> 00:41:10.800
I think that's, you know, I'd love to,

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:12.399
and I'd love to share that more widely.

00:41:12.479 --> 00:41:14.239
And I'd love to share that more widely

00:41:14.239 --> 00:41:16.959
with like, you know, folks I work with.

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:20.080
I think the problem that I have

00:41:20.080 --> 00:41:23.360
is that sharing them out to other people

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:25.919
is, you know, involves them

00:41:25.919 --> 00:41:28.000
having to save the right file

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:28.719
in the right place,

00:41:28.719 --> 00:41:31.520
which is always problematic for anybody, it seems.

00:41:32.399 --> 00:41:34.080
But you can set up your own,

00:41:34.080 --> 00:41:34.959
which is the great thing.

00:41:36.879 --> 00:41:37.679
Nice. Yeah.

00:41:37.679 --> 00:41:39.600
I was talking about that yesterday

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:41.679
with someone around, like,

00:41:41.679 --> 00:41:43.040
data products as well.

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:44.800
So like, if you had a template,

00:41:44.800 --> 00:41:47.840
like example, R Markdown or ShinyApp

00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:49.919
for something for your company

00:41:49.919 --> 00:41:52.159
and making it available for everyone to use.

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:55.520
Well, that's what a package is for, right?

00:41:57.600 --> 00:41:59.919
Well, I think like thinking about

00:41:59.919 --> 00:42:01.600
like having it published somewhere

00:42:01.600 --> 00:42:04.639
that you could just go and pull the sample app.

00:42:04.719 --> 00:42:08.560
Let me see if there are other questions

00:42:08.560 --> 00:42:10.239
that I didn't see on Slido yet.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:18.399
Oh, I see, Jen, you had asked a question

00:42:18.399 --> 00:42:20.159
in the chat too, if you want to jump in.

00:42:22.080 --> 00:42:23.120
Sure. Hey, Joe.

00:42:23.120 --> 00:42:23.679
Hey, Jen.

00:42:24.959 --> 00:42:25.919
It's good to see you.

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:28.080
I was going to ask,

00:42:28.080 --> 00:42:29.679
what's the most important traits

00:42:29.679 --> 00:42:31.040
that you look for when you hire?

00:42:31.040 --> 00:42:32.399
Like what questions do you ask

00:42:32.399 --> 00:42:34.000
to get that information?

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:40.959
Well, so when I hire,

00:42:40.959 --> 00:42:42.800
I'm not necessarily hiring a data scientist.

00:42:42.800 --> 00:42:44.320
I'm hiring an epidemiologist.

00:42:45.520 --> 00:42:47.520
And for an epidemiologist,

00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:51.360
I want somebody who, well,

00:42:52.239 --> 00:42:53.360
for a worker, I want somebody

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:54.800
who's going to take initiative,

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:59.040
who's going to be able to take the initiative

00:42:59.439 --> 00:43:02.719
who's going to be able to work independently

00:43:02.719 --> 00:43:03.760
or get to a point

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:05.439
where they can work independently.

00:43:07.520 --> 00:43:09.360
Who's got, you know, I don't know.

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:10.320
There's not one.

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:12.239
They're going to have to have good content knowledge.

00:43:14.080 --> 00:43:16.159
And yeah, I would love to be able

00:43:16.159 --> 00:43:18.879
to have x-ray vision where I can see

00:43:18.879 --> 00:43:20.080
that they're kind of like you, Jen,

00:43:20.080 --> 00:43:22.000
where they've got this amazing data brain

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:23.439
and they, you know, they go off to this stuff

00:43:23.439 --> 00:43:25.520
and they can, they understand, you know,

00:43:25.520 --> 00:43:27.360
they just sort of start to intuitively

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:28.399
understand data structures

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:30.320
and how to analyze stuff.

00:43:31.679 --> 00:43:33.919
But that's not necessarily essential.

00:43:34.879 --> 00:43:36.800
It's really more about people

00:43:36.800 --> 00:43:38.320
who are going to take initiative,

00:43:40.239 --> 00:43:41.439
be able to work independently

00:43:44.959 --> 00:43:45.679
and have some,

00:43:48.479 --> 00:43:50.879
have the right knowledge, at least.

00:43:50.879 --> 00:43:52.080
I love people with experience,

00:43:52.080 --> 00:43:53.199
but usually we end up just

00:43:53.199 --> 00:43:54.239
trying people out of school.

00:43:54.239 --> 00:43:56.879
So it's at least having sort of a basis of knowledge.

00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:00.159
And, well, and it's public health.

00:44:00.159 --> 00:44:01.840
So they've got to have the love for public health.

00:44:01.840 --> 00:44:02.959
They've got to be invested

00:44:03.520 --> 00:44:04.800
in what we're trying to get done.

00:44:04.800 --> 00:44:05.760
They've got to have the mission.

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:11.520
How do you interview for that

00:44:11.520 --> 00:44:13.679
to know if someone is going to

00:44:13.679 --> 00:44:14.719
take the initiative?

00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:20.879
We use a process called targeted selection

00:44:20.879 --> 00:44:22.000
that I picked up years ago.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.239
I used to work for Eli Lilly, the pharma company.

00:44:24.959 --> 00:44:26.239
And they gave me this training

00:44:26.239 --> 00:44:27.679
and this interview process.

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:31.439
But, you know, you lay out dimensions

00:44:31.439 --> 00:44:32.239
that are important,

00:44:32.239 --> 00:44:33.919
and then you have several different teams

00:44:33.919 --> 00:44:34.719
at different sessions

00:44:35.439 --> 00:44:36.639
ask about those dimensions.

00:44:36.639 --> 00:44:37.760
You have several people asking

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:39.439
about each dimension in different,

00:44:41.199 --> 00:44:41.760
separately.

00:44:41.760 --> 00:44:42.959
So you can combine,

00:44:42.959 --> 00:44:44.159
you can discuss afterwards.

00:44:45.199 --> 00:44:46.719
We make sure we ask for examples.

00:44:46.719 --> 00:44:49.520
We try to really nail people down to saying,

00:44:49.520 --> 00:44:51.520
tell me a specific situation

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:53.120
where you've been challenged with this

00:44:53.120 --> 00:44:54.000
and what did you do

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:54.959
and what was the result?

00:44:54.959 --> 00:44:56.080
As opposed to people saying,

00:44:56.639 --> 00:44:58.080
I'm really, I really like doing this.

00:44:58.080 --> 00:44:58.879
I'm really good at that.

00:44:58.879 --> 00:45:00.239
You know, just abstract talking

00:45:00.239 --> 00:45:01.600
and trying to get people down to

00:45:01.600 --> 00:45:03.600
talking about really a lot of specifics.

00:45:05.679 --> 00:45:07.199
And it's hard, but it's,

00:45:07.199 --> 00:45:09.280
I think probably the biggest tool

00:45:09.280 --> 00:45:11.840
I've used for making sure,

00:45:12.719 --> 00:45:13.919
seeing what people really have

00:45:13.919 --> 00:45:16.000
is asking them for specific examples

00:45:17.360 --> 00:45:18.879
and asking them.

00:45:18.879 --> 00:45:20.879
And it's called the star format.

00:45:20.879 --> 00:45:22.800
But you tell me what's the situation

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:23.600
or task you had

00:45:24.159 --> 00:45:25.120
what did you do about it?

00:45:25.120 --> 00:45:26.080
And what was the result?

00:45:26.719 --> 00:45:28.239
That illustrates your ability

00:45:28.239 --> 00:45:30.800
to whatever you're interested

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:31.840
in taking initiative

00:45:31.840 --> 00:45:33.280
or your investment

00:45:33.280 --> 00:45:34.639
in the mission of public health,

00:45:34.639 --> 00:45:35.760
whatever that might be.

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:41.120
Thanks, Joe.

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:45.760
I just want to check from the chat too.

00:45:45.760 --> 00:45:47.360
If I had missed your question,

00:45:47.360 --> 00:45:50.000
feel free to just raise your hand on Zoom too.

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:53.520
But one question I had for you, Joe,

00:45:54.399 --> 00:45:56.399
just based on a previous conversation

00:45:57.600 --> 00:45:59.600
is we talked a lot, a bit about

00:46:00.399 --> 00:46:01.840
like technical skills are important,

00:46:01.840 --> 00:46:03.280
but a lot of it is also learning

00:46:03.280 --> 00:46:06.639
how to partner with people as well.

00:46:06.639 --> 00:46:08.000
I was wondering if you could

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:09.199
chat a little bit about that.

00:46:10.239 --> 00:46:10.739
Yeah.

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:13.360
I've worked with people

00:46:13.360 --> 00:46:15.040
who have amazing technical ability

00:46:15.040 --> 00:46:17.600
and just super great data brains,

00:46:17.679 --> 00:46:18.719
great data brains,

00:46:18.719 --> 00:46:21.280
but at least at least in my field

00:46:21.280 --> 00:46:22.239
in epidemiology,

00:46:22.959 --> 00:46:24.879
it's all about producing information

00:46:25.520 --> 00:46:26.719
and it's about producing

00:46:26.719 --> 00:46:27.679
relevant information.

00:46:28.239 --> 00:46:30.080
So you've got to understand the customer.

00:46:30.080 --> 00:46:32.239
You've got to understand their situation

00:46:32.239 --> 00:46:34.959
and the better you understand

00:46:34.959 --> 00:46:35.919
where they're coming from,

00:46:35.919 --> 00:46:37.360
what they face day to day,

00:46:37.919 --> 00:46:39.360
the easier it is to add value

00:46:39.360 --> 00:46:40.560
to what they're doing

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:41.679
by bringing data to bear.

00:46:42.320 --> 00:46:43.919
I really see my group

00:46:44.479 --> 00:46:46.800
in Marin County as a support group,

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:48.000
as a service group.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:49.600
We're there to serve other people.

00:46:49.600 --> 00:46:50.879
Other people have the,

00:46:50.879 --> 00:46:52.080
they know what their problems are.

00:46:52.719 --> 00:46:55.760
We need to draw those problems out

00:46:55.760 --> 00:46:57.040
and understand what those problems are,

00:46:57.040 --> 00:46:58.479
kind of put them into our data language

00:46:58.479 --> 00:46:59.840
and then be able to apply data

00:46:59.840 --> 00:47:01.199
to those problems to get back

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:03.520
to their issues.

00:47:03.520 --> 00:47:06.159
So that's the partnership.

00:47:06.159 --> 00:47:07.120
That's the understanding.

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:08.000
You have to be really,

00:47:08.959 --> 00:47:10.560
the closer you are to the client,

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:10.959
the better.

00:47:10.959 --> 00:47:11.840
We've got some programs

00:47:11.840 --> 00:47:12.800
that are really well-funded.

00:47:12.800 --> 00:47:14.000
We can have one epi,

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:15.600
like spend most of their time

00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:17.120
on, say, HIV.

00:47:17.120 --> 00:47:18.479
We've got, Jen spends half,

00:47:19.280 --> 00:47:20.399
or she used to?

00:47:20.399 --> 00:47:20.899
Yeah.

00:47:22.719 --> 00:47:23.520
We have somebody who spends

00:47:23.520 --> 00:47:25.360
half of their time with HIV,

00:47:25.360 --> 00:47:26.639
with an HIV program.

00:47:27.280 --> 00:47:28.639
So they can sit with those people

00:47:28.639 --> 00:47:29.360
and really understand

00:47:29.360 --> 00:47:30.479
their day-to-day work

00:47:30.479 --> 00:47:32.239
and what the issues they face

00:47:32.239 --> 00:47:33.840
and see the opportunities

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:35.120
to bring data to bear on that.

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:35.840
So it's around

00:47:36.479 --> 00:47:37.679
really getting to know people

00:47:38.239 --> 00:47:39.280
so then you can translate

00:47:39.280 --> 00:47:42.239
their needs into data needs,

00:47:42.239 --> 00:47:44.000
pull the data and translate it,

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:44.639
give it to them.

00:47:46.560 --> 00:47:48.879
And create systems where, you know,

00:47:48.879 --> 00:47:49.679
it's not just answering

00:47:49.679 --> 00:47:50.479
individual questions,

00:47:50.479 --> 00:47:51.360
but it's creating systems

00:47:51.360 --> 00:47:52.239
where day-to-day,

00:47:52.239 --> 00:47:53.679
they can operate more effectively

00:47:53.679 --> 00:47:54.959
because you've set a system up

00:47:54.959 --> 00:47:55.840
where they get the information

00:47:55.840 --> 00:47:58.159
they need as they need it each day.

00:48:00.719 --> 00:48:01.520
Great, thank you.

00:48:02.479 --> 00:48:03.600
Well, I get to ask you

00:48:03.600 --> 00:48:04.479
more questions then

00:48:04.479 --> 00:48:06.080
if there aren't other questions

00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:06.879
from the audience.

00:48:07.679 --> 00:48:09.040
But I'm curious about

00:48:09.840 --> 00:48:11.919
your recent move

00:48:11.919 --> 00:48:14.080
to the Development Foundation

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:16.320
and how you made that decision

00:48:17.840 --> 00:48:19.439
after like moving

00:48:19.439 --> 00:48:20.639
into your leadership role

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:22.239
with the county.

00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:24.959
There's two things going on.

00:48:24.959 --> 00:48:27.199
One is just the whole issue

00:48:27.199 --> 00:48:28.639
of equity and racism.

00:48:29.439 --> 00:48:31.760
And this being just

00:48:31.760 --> 00:48:32.800
a really cool project

00:48:32.800 --> 00:48:34.320
to help try to help public health

00:48:34.320 --> 00:48:35.600
move along the pathway

00:48:35.600 --> 00:48:38.320
of addressing racism

00:48:38.320 --> 00:48:40.080
and equity more squarely.

00:48:41.040 --> 00:48:42.239
A lot of interest in

00:48:42.879 --> 00:48:45.600
integrating more equity-based practices

00:48:45.600 --> 00:48:46.639
and how we use data,

00:48:47.360 --> 00:48:48.479
what we do with data.

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:50.959
But within public health,

00:48:50.959 --> 00:48:52.000
there's a lot of discussion of that,

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:52.879
but we're still trying to figure out

00:48:52.879 --> 00:48:53.679
what it is.

00:48:53.679 --> 00:48:55.360
And this is an opportunity

00:48:55.360 --> 00:48:56.879
to put a lot of focus on figuring out

00:48:56.879 --> 00:48:58.399
what that might look like.

00:48:58.959 --> 00:49:00.719
And it's been a tremendous learning.

00:49:00.719 --> 00:49:02.000
I've had a tremendous amount of learning

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:02.959
over the last several months

00:49:02.959 --> 00:49:04.639
working with people who are much more

00:49:04.639 --> 00:49:07.280
in the racial equity workspace

00:49:07.280 --> 00:49:08.719
and advocacy area

00:49:08.719 --> 00:49:10.000
to figure out what it might mean.

00:49:10.159 --> 00:49:11.840
I always knew we need to be closer

00:49:11.840 --> 00:49:13.760
to the community than we were

00:49:13.760 --> 00:49:14.560
at Marion County.

00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:16.399
But the closer we were to the community,

00:49:16.399 --> 00:49:17.760
and again, this is getting back

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:18.959
to understanding the customer

00:49:18.959 --> 00:49:20.320
and understanding what the needs are out there

00:49:20.320 --> 00:49:21.360
and being relevant.

00:49:22.080 --> 00:49:23.120
The closer we are to them,

00:49:24.159 --> 00:49:25.199
the more relevant we're going to be,

00:49:25.199 --> 00:49:26.560
the more valuable what we produce

00:49:26.560 --> 00:49:27.360
is going to be.

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:29.360
And it's just been underscored

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:30.159
in the last several months

00:49:30.159 --> 00:49:31.600
about how important it is

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:34.320
to make the affected communities,

00:49:34.320 --> 00:49:35.919
the marginalized communities,

00:49:35.919 --> 00:49:37.840
partners in figuring out

00:49:37.840 --> 00:49:38.800
what the questions are,

00:49:39.040 --> 00:49:40.639
figuring out what the questions are

00:49:40.639 --> 00:49:41.520
and what the factors are

00:49:41.520 --> 00:49:42.399
you need to pull together

00:49:42.399 --> 00:49:44.159
in the information, the data,

00:49:44.159 --> 00:49:47.120
to identify, to bring to the surface

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:49.840
the issues like structural racism,

00:49:49.840 --> 00:49:51.439
how that's manifesting

00:49:51.439 --> 00:49:52.879
so that you can put a spotlight on that

00:49:52.879 --> 00:49:54.879
to try to bring about change

00:49:54.879 --> 00:49:57.600
and have them help frame the results

00:49:57.600 --> 00:50:00.080
in a way that's going to make that change move

00:50:00.080 --> 00:50:01.679
because they can frame the results

00:50:01.679 --> 00:50:04.800
in a really salient, impactful way,

00:50:04.800 --> 00:50:06.639
