It's really, so much of what I'm recognizing

00:50:55.199 --> 00:50:55.919
more and more is

00:50:58.959 --> 00:50:59.760
the problem with race,

00:51:00.959 --> 00:51:02.959
things that perpetuate racism

00:51:02.959 --> 00:51:04.159
and structural racism

00:51:04.719 --> 00:51:07.439
are that we don't talk about it,

00:51:07.439 --> 00:51:09.280
we ignore it, we don't label it.

00:51:12.560 --> 00:51:14.159
And that's not okay

00:51:14.159 --> 00:51:16.000
because that allows it to continue.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:17.760
If we really want to change

00:51:17.760 --> 00:51:19.040
what's happening,

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:23.280
we need to talk about white privilege

00:51:23.280 --> 00:51:24.000
and about how,

00:51:25.520 --> 00:51:27.120
like, again, I'm in public health,

00:51:27.120 --> 00:51:28.959
so how a lot of the differences

00:51:28.959 --> 00:51:30.639
we see in statistics

00:51:30.639 --> 00:51:31.520
rather than just presenting,

00:51:31.520 --> 00:51:32.879
okay, there's this difference in white,

00:51:33.120 --> 00:51:34.239
in terms of health outcomes,

00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:36.479
frame that in the context

00:51:36.479 --> 00:51:39.600
of we've got 400 years of history

00:51:40.239 --> 00:51:42.959
where this group has been oppressed

00:51:42.959 --> 00:51:43.679
in many ways.

00:51:43.679 --> 00:51:46.239
We've had, and not just before,

00:51:46.239 --> 00:51:48.800
not just until the Civil War,

00:51:48.800 --> 00:51:50.399
but there's redlining,

00:51:50.399 --> 00:51:52.080
there's all sorts of,

00:51:52.080 --> 00:51:53.040
there's the implementation

00:51:53.040 --> 00:51:58.399
of like the whatever, World War II,

00:51:59.120 --> 00:52:01.520
veterans, the veterans benefits

00:52:01.520 --> 00:52:02.639
and such like that.

00:52:02.639 --> 00:52:03.439
There's a lot of stuff

00:52:03.439 --> 00:52:05.679
that just really left out these communities.

00:52:05.679 --> 00:52:06.399
Social security,

00:52:06.399 --> 00:52:08.159
when social security was implemented,

00:52:08.159 --> 00:52:10.399
it excluded domestic workers

00:52:10.399 --> 00:52:11.840
and agricultural workers,

00:52:11.840 --> 00:52:13.360
which are white and black

00:52:13.360 --> 00:52:14.399
and all different colors,

00:52:14.399 --> 00:52:16.639
but most of them were different colors than white.

00:52:16.639 --> 00:52:18.239
And so the net effect of that

00:52:18.800 --> 00:52:21.120
was to oppress certain groups

00:52:21.120 --> 00:52:22.159
much more than other groups.

00:52:22.719 --> 00:52:24.080
So bringing that to the surface

00:52:24.080 --> 00:52:25.520
when we present results

00:52:25.520 --> 00:52:27.520
to frame it in more context

00:52:28.159 --> 00:52:28.959
where people can see

00:52:29.679 --> 00:52:30.800
the structural racism,

00:52:30.800 --> 00:52:32.959
the effects of the structural racism

00:52:32.959 --> 00:52:35.360
to push us toward thinking about

00:52:35.360 --> 00:52:36.639
how to address those issues.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:41.199
It's not just a woman lives in a house

00:52:41.199 --> 00:52:42.479
that has a lot of asthma triggers.

00:52:42.479 --> 00:52:43.679
It's, there's a lot of dust,

00:52:43.679 --> 00:52:45.120
there might be cockroaches, whatever.

00:52:46.080 --> 00:52:47.760
We go and we can intervene

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:48.639
to improve that house

00:52:48.639 --> 00:52:50.239
or move to a different house

00:52:50.239 --> 00:52:51.120
and that helps her.

00:52:51.919 --> 00:52:53.199
But we need to get back to

00:52:53.199 --> 00:52:54.239
why do we have people

00:52:54.239 --> 00:52:55.360
living in houses like that?

00:52:55.360 --> 00:52:57.120
We need to change the policies

00:52:57.120 --> 00:52:58.560
that are allowing

00:52:58.560 --> 00:53:00.560
these inequities to occur.

00:53:00.560 --> 00:53:02.000
And so it's trying to push back

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:05.840
to more root causes of the issues

00:53:05.840 --> 00:53:06.800
that we're trying to deal with.

